SIMPLE: sedge
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sedge
<hw>Sedge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>segge</ets>,
AS. <ets>secg</ets>; akin to LG. <ets>segge</ets>; -- probably named
from its bladelike appearance, and akin to L. <ets>secare</ets> to cut,
E. <ets>saw</ets> a cutting instrument; cf. Ir. <ets>seisg</ets>, W.
<ets>hesg</ets>. Cf. <er>Hassock</er>, <er>Saw</er> the
instrument.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any plant of the
genus <gen>Carex</gen>, perennial, endogenous, innutritious herbs, often
growing in dense tufts in marshy places. They have triangular jointless
stems, a spiked inflorescence, and long grasslike leaves which are
usually rough on the margins and midrib. There are several hundred
species.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The name is sometimes given to any other plant of the
order <ord>Cyperaceae</ord>, which includes <gen>Carex</gen>,
<gen>Cyperus</gen>, <gen>Scirpus</gen>, and many other genera of
rushlike plants.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A flock of herons.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sedge hen</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the clapper
rail. See under 5th <er>Rail</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sedge
warbler</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small European singing bird
(<spn>Acrocephalus phragmitis</spn>). It often builds its nest among
reeds; -- called also <altname>sedge bird</altname>, <altname>sedge
wren</altname>, <altname>night warbler</altname>, and <altname>Scotch
nightingale</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sedged</ent>⟦br⟧
